SIMPLE: hearts-ease
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hearts-ease
<hw>Heart's"-ease`</hw> <pr>(h⟦aum⟧rts"⟦emac⟧z`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Ease of heart; peace or tranquillity of mind or
feeling.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A species of violet (<spn>Viola
tricolor</spn>), a common and long cultivated European herb from which
most common garden pansies are derived; -- called also
<altname>pansy</altname>.</def> <wns>[wns=1]</wns>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> wild pansy, Johnny-jump-up, heartsease,
love-in-idleness, pink of my John, Viola tricolor.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A violet of the Pacific coast of
North America (<spn>Viola ocellata</spn>) having white petals tinged
with yellow and deep violet.</def> <wns>[wns=2]</wns>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> two-eyed violet, heartsease, <spn>Viola
ocellata</spn>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A common Old World viola
(<spn>Viola arvensis</spn>) with creamy often violet-tinged
flowers.</def> <wns>[wns=3]</wns>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> field pansy, heartsease, <spn>Viola
arvensis</spn>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Heartseed</ent>⟦br⟧
